    date: "2024-10-01",
    readTime: "10 min read",
    imageGradient: "linear-gradient(135deg, #e07b3a 0%, #fbc607 100%)",
    imageUrl: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1460925895917-afdab827c52f?w=800&h=600&fit=crop",
    content: [
      { heading: "Data Modeling: Where Most Projects Go Wrong", body: "Get the data model right and most other decisions become easier. Get it wrong and every feature becomes a fight against your own schema. production software For enterprise software, the most common mistake we see is modeling the current state of the business instead of modeling the events that produced that state. Event-sourced models are more work upfront but pay dividends every time the business changes a rule, asks for an audit trail, or wants to replay history. We'll show you the schema patterns we use and the three times we got it badly wrong." },
      { heading: "Testing Strategy That Actually Catches Bugs", body: "Most test suites we inherit are theater - they pass on every commit and catch almost nothing. production software The problem isn't the tests themselves; it's what they test. Unit tests on pure functions are easy and useless. Integration tests on real dependencies are hard and valuable. End-to-end tests catch the bugs users actually hit but are flaky and slow. The right ratio for enterprise software is heavily weighted toward integration tests, with a thin layer of E2E covering the critical user paths. We'll share the test pyramid we actually use, the tooling that makes it maintainable, and the metrics that tell us when our tests are lying." },
      { heading: "The Architecture Conversation", body: "Architecture is the set of decisions that are expensive to change later. Everything else is implementation. production software The mistake we see most often in enterprise software is teams optimizing for the wrong axis - choosing a database because it's trendy, or a service boundary because it looked clean in a diagram. Good architecture starts from constraints: what's your team size, your traffic profile, your latency budget, your operational maturity? A two-person team building enterprise software for ten thousand users should make completely different choices than a fifty-person team building for ten million. We'll walk through the decision framework we use." },
      { heading: "What We'd Tell Our Younger Selves", body: "If we could send a message back to ourselves starting enterprise software five years ago, it would be short: invest in observability before features, push back on requirements that smell wrong, write the boring integration test, and ship smaller. production software The instinct to build flexible abstractions is almost always wrong. Build the specific thing, ship it, watch how users actually use it, then abstract. We've deleted more abstraction than we've shipped. The code that has survived in our enterprise software projects is plain, obvious, and slightly verbose - and it's the code we can debug at 3 AM." },
      { heading: "The Build vs Buy Decision", body: "Every enterprise software project reaches a moment where someone asks: should we build this or use a SaaS? The honest answer is almost always 'it depends,' but the way you analyze the decision matters more than the conclusion. production software We use a simple framework: total cost of ownership over three years, including maintenance, opportunity cost, and exit cost. The exit cost is the one most teams ignore - what happens if the vendor raises prices 5x, gets acquired by a competitor, or shuts down? We've helped three clients migrate off vendors that went sideways, and the migration cost was always higher than the build cost would have been." },
      { heading: "Operations: What Happens After Launch", body: "Software doesn't end at deployment - that's where it begins. production software The operational patterns we use for enterprise software were hard-won through incidents at 2 AM, customer escalations, and the slow accumulation of pager fatigue. The fundamentals are boring and essential: dashboards that show business metrics (not just technical ones), runbooks that a junior on-call can follow, postmortems that produce system changes (not blame), and a deployment pipeline that makes pushing the fix easier than the original deploy. We'll share the operational template we apply to every project before we hand it over." },
    ],
