    slug: "why-your-onboarding-flow-is-too-long",
    title: "Why Your Onboarding Flow Is Too Long",
    excerpt: "What we've learned designing products that real users love - drawn from 80+ product design engagements across fintech, healthcare, retail, and SaaS.",
    category: "UI/UX Design",
    author: { name: "Tanvi Bhat", role: "3D Artist", avatarGradient: "linear-gradient(135deg, #e07b3a, #fbc607)" },
    date: "2024-03-15",
    readTime: "14 min read",
    imageGradient: "linear-gradient(135deg, #f59e0b 0%, #fbc607 100%)",
    imageUrl: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1557804506-669a67965ba0?w=800&h=600&fit=crop",
    content: [
      { heading: "When to Break the Rules", body: "Design rules - 'don't use modals,' 'always show the price,' 'keep forms short' - exist for good reasons. But rules are defaults, not laws. design systems The most interesting product design design work happens when you understand why a rule exists, identify the specific case where it doesn't apply, and break it deliberately. We'll share cases where breaking conventional wisdom produced better outcomes - and the analysis we did beforehand to know it would work. The lesson isn't 'break rules' - it's 'understand rules deeply enough to know when they don't apply.'" },
      { heading: "Starting From the User", body: "Good product design design starts with understanding the user - not as a persona on a wall, but as a real person with goals, constraints, and a phone they're trying to use one-handed on a Bangalore bus. design systems We invest in research before pixels: interviews, contextual inquiry, diary studies, and analytics review. The patterns we ship for product design are grounded in what users actually do, not what they say they want. We'll share the research methods we use, the cadence we run them at, and how we translate findings into design decisions." },
      { heading: "Micro-Interactions: The Details That Matter", body: "The difference between a good product and a great one is in the micro-interactions - the button that acknowledges your click, the loading state that doesn't feel broken, the form that highlights errors helpfully. design systems We spend disproportionate time on product design micro-interactions because they're what users feel, even if they can't articulate why. A 200ms animation that confirms an action can be the difference between a user trusting your product and not. We'll share the micro-interaction patterns we use and the principles behind them." },
      { heading: "The Design System Investment", body: "A design system pays off when you have more than three product surfaces and more than two designers. Below that, it's overhead. design systems For product design, we build design systems iteratively - starting with tokens (color, spacing, typography), then primitives (buttons, inputs, cards), then patterns (forms, navigation, data display). The system lives in Figma and code, synchronized by tooling. The investment is significant - 4-8 weeks for a v1 - but the payoff is faster shipping, consistent UX, and a vocabulary the whole team shares." },
      { heading: "Measuring Design Impact", body: "Design without measurement is art. Design with measurement is product. design systems For every product design design decision, we define the metric we're trying to move - conversion, retention, task completion, satisfaction - and we instrument it. We A/B test where it makes sense, and we watch analytics where it doesn't. The result is a design function that can defend its decisions with data and learn from what doesn't work. We'll share the metrics framework we use and the dashboards we build for every project." },
      { heading: "Accessibility Is Not a Phase", body: "Designing accessible product design isn't something you check at the end - it's a constraint from the start. design systems We design for keyboard navigation, screen reader compatibility, color contrast, and cognitive load from the first wireframe. The cost of catching accessibility issues in design is 10x lower than catching them in QA, and 100x lower than catching them after launch. We'll share the accessibility checklist we run through on every design review, and the tools we use to verify compliance." },
    ],
