    slug: "how-we-took-a-saas-from-page-5-to-page-1-in-6-months",
    title: "How We Took a SaaS From Page 5 to Page 1 in 6 Months",
    excerpt: "Real marketing lessons from driving growth for B2B and D2C clients - SEO, content, paid, and the metrics that actually matter.",
    category: "Marketing",
    author: { name: "Yashraj Kumar", role: "Principal Engineer", avatarGradient: "linear-gradient(135deg, #f59e0b, #fbc607)" },
    date: "2021-06-08",
    readTime: "11 min read",
    imageGradient: "linear-gradient(135deg, #e07b3a 0%, #fbc607 100%)",
    imageUrl: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1611926653458-09294b3142bf?w=800&h=600&fit=crop",
    content: [
      { heading: "Starting From Strategy", body: "Marketing without strategy is just activity. performance marketing Every growth marketing marketing engagement starts with positioning: who's the buyer, what's the alternative, why you? Without clear positioning, every channel decision becomes a guess. We work with clients to nail positioning first - usually in a one-week sprint - and then build the channel mix around it. The result is marketing that compounds instead of marketing that just spends. We'll share the positioning framework we use." },
      { heading: "SEO: The Long Game That Pays Off", body: "SEO is the highest-ROI channel for most B2B and D2C businesses - but it takes 6-12 months to show results, which is why most teams underinvest. performance marketing For growth marketing, we approach SEO as a content and technical discipline: keyword research grounded in actual search intent, content that comprehensively answers the query, technical SEO that makes the site crawlable and fast, and link-building through genuine authority. We'll share the SEO playbook we use, the timelines we set, and the metrics that tell us it's working." },
      { heading: "Paid: When and How", body: "Paid marketing is a multiplier on something that already works. performance marketing If your growth marketing positioning is wrong, paid amplifies the wrong message. If your landing page converts at 0.5%, paid just brings more people to a leaky funnel. We use paid when: the organic funnel is proven, the unit economics work, and the goal is scale. We avoid paid when: the team is small, the product is early, or the goal is learning. We'll share the paid framework we use and the campaigns we've run." },
      { heading: "What We'd Do Differently", body: "If we were starting a growth marketing marketing function from scratch today, we'd: invest in SEO from day one (it takes too long to start later), build an email list before we needed it, say no to most paid experiments, hire a writer before a designer, and measure everything against pipeline - not vanity metrics. performance marketing The marketing playbooks that worked in 2020 don't work in 2026. Attention has fragmented, AI has flooded content channels, and buyers are more skeptical. The fundamentals - clear positioning, genuine authority, helpful content - work better than ever. The tactics are constantly changing." },
      { heading: "Content as a Moat", body: "Content is the only marketing investment that compounds. Paid stops the moment you stop paying. Social reach decays. Email lists churn. But a growth marketing article that ranks and earns links keeps producing value for years. performance marketing We invest in content accordingly: long-form, comprehensive, evergreen, and genuinely useful. The bar is high - we won't publish something if we can't make it the best resource on the topic. We'll share the content production process, the editorial standards, and the analytics we use to measure content ROI." },
      { heading: "Marketing Attribution", body: "Attribution is the hardest problem in marketing - and the most important. performance marketing Last-click attribution (which most analytics tools default to) over-credits the last touch and under-credits everything that came before. Multi-touch attribution is better but complex. For growth marketing, we use a pragmatic approach: first-touch for awareness, last-touch for conversion, and self-reported attribution ('how did you hear about us?') for the truth that analytics can't capture. We'll share the attribution model we use and the dashboards we build." },
    ],
